{"type":"message","id":"5f7075e1","parentId":"ed9c4801","timestamp":"2026-03-31T16:45:30.290Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I should create a references directory with some helpful documentation.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_78903790bf4e48af98286ba4","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/home/ivo/.openclaw/workspace/skills/research/references/best_practices.md","content":"# Research Best Practices\n\n## Planning Your Research\n\n### 1. Define Clear Objectives\n- Start with specific research questions\n- What exactly do you need to know?\n- How will you use the information?\n- What constitutes \"enough\" research?\n\n### 2. Scope Your Research\n- Set boundaries: time period, geographic focus, source types\n- Determine depth vs. breadth trade-offs\n- Identify what's out of scope\n\n### 3. Choose Methodology\n- Qualitative vs. quantitative approaches\n- Primary vs. secondary sources\n- Experimental vs. observational\n\n## Source Evaluation\n\n### 1. Authority and Credibility\n- Who created the source? What are their qualifications?\n- Is the source peer-reviewed or editorially reviewed?\n- What is the reputation of the publication/platform?\n\n### 2. Accuracy and Reliability\n- Can information be verified through other sources?\n- Are claims supported by evidence?\n- Are there citations or references to original research?\n\n### 3. Objectivity and Bias\n- What is the purpose of the source? (Inform, persuade, sell, entertain)\n- Are multiple viewpoints presented?\n- Is language neutral or emotionally charged?\n- Who funded the research or content creation?\n\n### 4. Currency and Relevance\n- When was the source published or last updated?\n- Is the information still current for your topic?\n- Does it directly address your research question?\n\n## Information Organization\n\n### 1. Note-Taking Systems\n- Use consistent formatting for notes\n- Include source citations with every note\n- Distinguish between direct quotes and paraphrasing\n- Note your own thoughts and reactions separately\n\n### 2. Digital Organization\n- Use descriptive filenames and folder structures\n- Tag sources by topic, type, and relevance\n- Maintain a master bibliography or source list\n- Use reference management tools when appropriate\n\n### 3. Synthesis Techniques\n- Create concept maps or mind maps\n- Develop outlines before writing\n- Use comparison charts for contrasting viewpoints\n- Identify patterns, trends, and gaps in information\n\n## Ethical Considerations\n\n### 1. Academic Integrity\n- Always cite your sources properly\n- Never present others' work as your own\n- Understand and follow citation conventions for your field\n- When in doubt, cite the source\n\n### 2. Respect for Intellectual Property\n- Follow fair use guidelines for copyrighted material\n- Seek permission when needed for substantial use\n- Respect licenses and terms of use for digital content\n- Give credit for ideas, not just direct quotes\n\n### 3. Responsible Use of Information\n- Consider potential impacts of sharing sensitive information\n- Verify information before sharing it with others\n- Be transparent about limitations and uncertainties in your findings\n- Correct errors promptly when discovered\n\n## Research Workflow Optimization\n\n### 1. Iterative Approach\n- Start broad, then narrow based on findings\n- Let early results inform later search strategies\n- Be willing to revise research questions as you learn\n- Build in time for reflection and synthesis\n\n### 2. Efficient Searching\n- Use advanced search operators (quotes, AND/OR/NOT, site:, filetype:)\n- Try synonyms and related terms\n- Mine bibliographies of good sources for more references\n- Set up alerts for ongoing topics\n\n### 3. Managing Information Overload\n- Set time limits for initial gathering phases\n- Use skimming and scanning techniques effectively\n- Develop quick evaluation heuristics\n- Take regular breaks to maintain focus\n\n### 4. Collaboration and Feedback\n- Discuss findings with peers or mentors\n- Seek feedback on your research approach\n- Consider different perspectives on your topic\n- Share preliminary findings for validation\n\n## Specific to Available Tools\n\n### YouTube Research\n- Check multiple videos on same topic for consistency\n- Look at video comments for additional resources or critiques\n- Consider upload date and view count as quality indicators\n- Transcripts may contain errors - verify key points\n\n### NotebookLM Research\n- Start with high-quality, diverse sources\n- Use specific, focused queries rather than vague questions\n- Take advantage of AI-generated summaries but verify claims\n- Experiment with different artifact types for different purposes\n\n### General Web Research\n- Go beyond first page of search results\n- Use specialized search engines for specific topics (scholar, news, etc.)\n- Check domain authority (.edu, .gov, reputable .org)\n- Use Wayback Machine for inaccessible or changed content\n\n## Documentation and Reproducibility\n\n### 1. Research Log\n- Keep track of search terms used and when\n- Note which sources were consulted and rejected\n- Record any obstacles or dead ends encountered\n- Document decisions about source inclusion/exclusion\n\n### 2. Source Tracking\n- Maintain a working bibliography from the start\n- Include all necessary citation information\n- Note access dates for online sources\n- Use consistent citation format throughout\n\n### 3. Process Documentation\n- Describe your research methodology\n- Note any tools or techniques used\n- Record deviations from original plan\n- Explain how you synthesized information\n\n## Quality Assurance\n\n### 1. Triangulation\n- Seek confirmation from multiple independent sources\n- Look for convergence of evidence from different methodologies\n- Be wary of single-source claims, especially surprising ones\n\n### 2. Peer Review\n- Have others check your work for obvious errors\n- Consider alternative interpretations of your findings\n- Be open to revising conclusions based on feedback\n\n### 3. Self-Check\n- Review your work for logical consistency\n- Check that conclusions follow from evidence presented\n- Verify that you haven't ignored contradictory evidence\n- Ensure proper attribution throughout\n\n## Adapting to Different Research Types\n\n### 1. Fact-Finding Research\n- Prioritize authoritative sources\n- Cross-check facts across multiple references\n- Note any uncertainties or disputed information\n- Focus on accuracy and precision\n\n### 2. Exploratory Research\n- Cast a wide net initially\n- Follow interesting leads as they emerge\n- Be open to unexpected connections\n- Document your journey of discovery\n\n### 3. Comparative Research\n- Establish clear comparison criteria\n- Ensure sources are comparable in quality and type\n- Look for both similarities and differences\n- Consider context when making comparisons\n\n### 4. Problem-Solving Research\n- Define the problem clearly before searching\n- Look for proven solutions and best practices\n- Consider implementation challenges and trade-offs\n- Seek both theoretical and practical guidance"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b","usage":{"input":18298,"output":1403,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19701,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774975459467,"responseId":"chatcmpl-a7c367d0315f3a7c"}}
